          "title": "The heart that the chapter cannot see — and what that means",
          "body": "Proverbs 14 makes a philosophically precise claim about interiority in verse 10: *the heart knows its own bitterness, and a stranger does not share its joy.* This is not sentimentality; it is epistemology. The inner life of another person is radically inaccessible. This observation is immediately subverted in verse 13: even your *own* laughter may conceal heart-pain you are not fully reading accurately. Together, 14:10 and 14:13 frame the problem that 14:12 names theologically: if we cannot fully know another's heart, and our own laughter may mask our own pain, then the way that *seems* right to *a man* (14:12) — the way that feels correct from inside — cannot be the ultimate arbiter of which path to take. This is why 14:26-27 names the *fear of the LORD* as the indispensable orientation: only the one who brings his self-assessment before the living God gets the outside corrective the inner life cannot supply."
