          "body": "The cluster of 14:20-22 and 14:31 is the chapter's most socially demanding section, and it works by escalation. Verse 20 is descriptive realism: the poor are socially marginalized. Verse 21 converts that observation into moral verdict: to *despise* the neighbor in low circumstances is named as *sin* (*chata*), and graciousness to the poor is declared *blessed*. Verse 31 delivers the theological payoff: oppressing the poor is not merely unkind — it *taunts* (*charaph*, reproaches) the God who made the poor person. The logic is covenantal and creational simultaneously. Since every poor person is made by the same God who made the oppressor, to treat the poor with contempt is to reflect on the competence and honor of their Maker. Conversely, honoring the poor person *in their poverty* honors God. Derek Kidner (Proverbs, TOTC) observes that this is one of the points where Old Testament Wisdom and Old Testament Prophecy converge: Amos and Proverbs are measuring the same social failure by the same standard."
