        "title": "Wisdom builds; folly tears down — the household as the primary test of character",
        "range": "14:1-4",
        "excerpt": "The wise woman builds her house, but the foolish tears it down with her own hands.",
        "body": "The chapter's opening couplet (14:1) is one of the most compressed images in the entire Proverbs collection. The Hebrew places *chokhmot nashim* (wisdoms of women, a plural of intensity sometimes rendered 'the wisest of women') against *ivvelet* (folly personified as a foolish woman). Both are building and destroying the same *bet* — the household, which in ancient Israel encompassed family structure, economic stability, social standing, and covenantal faithfulness. The wise woman's building is active and cumulative; the foolish woman's tearing-down is reflexive — *with her own hands*. The hands that could build are the instruments of destruction.\n\nVerse 14:2 immediately anchors this household-level observation in the vertical relationship: the one who walks in uprightness *fears the LORD*; the one who is devious in his ways *despises* (*bazah*, holds in contempt) Him. The parallelism is precise. Uprightness of walk = fear of the LORD. Devious ways = despising God. Moral character is not merely a social or relational quality; it is the visible expression of one's true posture toward God. This is the first explicit mention of the fear of the LORD in the chapter, anticipating its full theological development in 14:26-27.\n\nVerse 14:4 — one of the most practically grounded couplets in the chapter — makes a point that cuts against the Pharisaical tidiness that can masquerade as wisdom. Where there are no oxen the manger is clean, but much revenue comes by the strength of the ox. Derek Kidner (Proverbs, TOTC) calls this 'a principle of life itself: everything has its price.' The clean manger is the price of having no ox; fruitlessness is what you get when you have avoided the mess of productive partnership. The proverb argues against a false wisdom that equates tidiness with virtue and discomfort with folly. Real wisdom accepts the cost of productive risk.\n\nTogether, verses 1-4 establish the chapter's opening thesis: wisdom is constructive, productive, and vertically grounded; folly is destructive, sterile, and theologically rootless. The household is the primary laboratory where this is tested and seen — first in the woman who builds or tears down (14:1), then in the man whose walk reveals his theology (14:2), then in the farmer who either has an ox or a clean manger (14:4).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chokhmot nashim* in 14:1 is a plural of intensity — 'the wisest women,' the summit of wisdom expressed in female form. *Bazah* (despises, 14:2) is the word used of Esau despising his birthright (Gen 25:34) and of those who despise the covenant sacrifices (1 Sam 2:17) — contempt directed at something sacred. *Bet* (house, 14:1, 11) encompasses the entire household and its social network, not merely the physical structure."
